            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this depth of field calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool uses the classic thin-lens depth of field formulas
                used by many professional DOF calculators and photography
                references. All internal calculations are done in millimeters.
              </p>

              <h3>Key formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Hyperfocal distance</strong> (in mm):</p>
                <p>$$H = \frac{f^2}{N \cdot c} + f$$</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(f\) = focal length (mm)</li>
                  <li>\(N\) = f-number (aperture)</li>
                  <li>\(c\) = circle of confusion (mm)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  <strong>Near focus limit</strong> at subject distance \(s\):
                </p>
                <p>$$D_\text{near} = \frac{H \cdot s}{H + (s - f)}$$</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Far focus limit</strong> at subject distance \(s\):
                </p>
                <p>
                  If \(s &lt; H\):<br />
                  $$D_\text{far} = \frac{H \cdot s}{H - (s - f)}$$
                </p>
                <p>If \(s \ge H\), the far limit is effectively at infinity.</p>
                <p><strong>Total depth of field</strong>:</p>
                <p>$$\text{DOF} = D_\text{far} - D_\text{near}$$</p>
              </div>

              <p>
                For blur at the subject and background distances, the calculator
                estimates the circle-of-confusion diameter on the sensor using
                the magnification at each distance and the chosen circle of
                confusion threshold.
              </p>

              <h2>What is depth of field?</h2>
              <p>
                Depth of field (DOF) is the distance between the nearest and
                farthest points in a scene that appear acceptably sharp in your
                photo. Objects inside this zone look sharp; objects in front of
                or behind it become increasingly blurred.
              </p>
              <p>
                DOF is not a hard boundary. It is defined using a
                <em>circle of confusion</em> threshold: the largest blur circle
                that still looks sharp at a given viewing size and distance.
                That’s why this calculator lets you choose or customize the
                circle of confusion.
              </p>

              <h3>Factors that control depth of field</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Aperture (f-number)</strong> – Wider apertures (small
                  f-numbers like f/1.4) give shallower DOF and stronger
                  background blur. Narrow apertures (large f-numbers like f/11)
                  increase DOF.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Focal length</strong> – Longer focal lengths (e.g. 85
                  mm, 200 mm) give shallower DOF at the same framing and
                  distance than shorter focal lengths.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Subject distance</strong> – The closer you focus, the
                  shallower the DOF. Macro distances can produce extremely thin
                  DOF.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sensor size / circle of confusion</strong> – For the
                  same framing and aperture, smaller sensors produce deeper DOF
                  than larger sensors.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Hyperfocal distance explained</h2>
              <p>
                Hyperfocal distance is the closest distance you can focus such
                that objects at infinity are still acceptably sharp. If you
                focus at the hyperfocal distance:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Everything from about
                  <strong>half the hyperfocal distance</strong> to infinity will
                  be in focus.
                </li>
                <li>
                  This is ideal for
                  <strong>landscape and street photography</strong> where you
                  want maximum DOF.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the hyperfocal distance from the calculator, set your focus
                manually to that distance on your lens scale (or as close as
                possible), and then compose your shot.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical DOF tips</h2>
              <h3>For portraits (shallow DOF &amp; bokeh)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Use a <strong>wide aperture</strong> (f/1.2–f/2.8).</li>
                <li>
                  Choose a <strong>longer focal length</strong> (e.g. 85–135 mm
                  on full-frame).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Move <strong>closer to your subject</strong> and keep the
                  background far behind them.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use a <strong>larger sensor</strong> camera if possible for
                  even shallower DOF.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>For landscapes (maximum DOF)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use a <strong>moderately narrow aperture</strong> (f/8–f/11).
                  Going too narrow (f/22) can soften the image due to
                  diffraction.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Focus at or slightly beyond the
                  <strong>hyperfocal distance</strong> reported by the
                  calculator.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use a <strong>wider lens</strong> (e.g. 16–35 mm) to naturally
                  increase DOF.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Uses the <strong>thin-lens approximation</strong>, which is
                  very accurate for most real-world photography except extreme
                  macro.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Assumes a <strong>flat subject plane</strong> perpendicular to
                  the lens axis.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Circle of confusion presets are typical values; perceived
                  sharpness also depends on
                  <strong>print size and viewing distance</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Depth of field FAQ</h2>

              <h3>
                Why does my real photo look different from the calculator?
              </h3>
              <p>
                DOF formulas are based on geometric optics and an assumed
                viewing condition. Real photos can look slightly different
                because of lens design, diffraction, sensor resolution,
                sharpening, and how large you view the image. Use the calculator
                as a precise guide, then fine-tune based on your own camera and
                style.
              </p>

              <h3>What circle of confusion value should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                The presets (e.g. 0.03 mm for full-frame) are standard values
                used in many DOF tables. If you print very large or view images
                very close, you may want a <strong>smaller</strong> CoC
                (stricter sharpness). For web-sized images or small prints, the
                default values are usually fine.
              </p>

              <h3>Is depth of field symmetric around the focus distance?</h3>
              <p>
                No. In most real situations, more of the DOF lies
                <strong>behind</strong> the focus point than in front of it,
                especially at longer distances. The calculator shows this split
                as “in front of subject” and “behind subject”.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for smartphone cameras?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Choose the smartphone preset or enter a small circle of
                confusion (around 0.005–0.01 mm). Keep in mind that phones also
                use computational blur, which is not modeled by optical DOF
                formulas.
              </p>
            </section>
